body:
After a three-week wait, â€œSouth Parkâ€ is back with a new episode and a new season.

	In an abrupt turn of events, the short-lived Season 27 has ended after just five episodes, instead of the previously determined 10, a spokesperson for Comedy Central confirmed. No details were provided as to why. Wednesdayâ€™s Season 28 premiere saw South Park Elementary enveloped in the â€œ6-7â€ TikTok trend, and Palantir co-founder Peter Thiel thinks the Antichrist is to blame.
	

	The episode opens on a rally led by PC Principal, who is determined to get South Park Elementary back on track after catching wind of some â€œsantaic numerology shitâ€ going on.â€ To set things straight, he brings in a guest speaker to talk some sense into the student body: The â€œabsolute expert on the end of days and the coming of the Antichrist,â€ Peter Thiel.


	â€œHello, kids, Iâ€™m Peter Thiel, and Iâ€™m here to talk to you about the Antichrist,â€ he says. â€œOk, so first, what is the Antichrist? The Antichrist is a newer, more human form of Satan that will soon walk the Earth. We donâ€™t know how soon it will walk the Earth, but it could be within the next six to seven weeks.â€

	The South Park Elementary student body then explodes in unison, â€œ6-7!â€

	Confused, Thiel continues his impromptu TED Talk. He explains that Satan wasnâ€™t able to have a child until Donald Trump came along, who has the perfect-sized manhood to fit inside Satanâ€™s â€œpinholeâ€ sized rectum. How big is Trumpâ€™s manhood? Thiel estimates itâ€™s between â€œsix and seven centimeters.â€

	Once again, his Gen Alpha audience shouts, â€œ6-7!â€

	Now frustrated, Thiel yells back at the kids, â€œThe Antichrist is coming! The Bible refers to the eagle, which refers to America, the fourth seal broken, and hell coming to Earth. Itâ€™s right here in Revelations Sixâ€¦ Six-Seven.â€
	

	Dead set on putting an end to the seemingly demonic â€œ6-7â€ craze, Thiel dives into the school data center with PC Principal and South Park Elementaryâ€™s counselor, Jesus Christ, to look for answers.

	â€œIâ€™ve downloaded all the studentsâ€™ information and loaded them into an AI face detection program so the schoolâ€™s security cameras can watch their every move,â€ he says. â€œNow look. Two students passing each other in the hallway. They give each other the sign: six, seven. Exactly 67 seconds later, this odd parka-wearing child makes the same gesture. And then inside the girlsâ€™ bathroom, two girls doing the same thing!â€

	A concerned Jesus stops him, â€œWait, why is there a camera inside the girlsâ€™ bathroom?â€

	Thiel returns, â€œTo stop the Antichrist!â€

	All the while, Thiel has been secretly working for JD Vance, who is determined to stop the Antichrist from being born so that he can take Trumpâ€™s place instead of the devil child. He tells Vance, while en route to a child he suspects is connected to the demon spawn, â€œIâ€™m very close to finding the secret of the numbers. Iâ€™ve narrowed it down to one little boy who seems more possessed than the others.â€

	The child in question: Eric Cartman.

	Ala â€œThe Exorcist,â€ Thiel walks up to Cartmanâ€™s room to free him from the possession.

	Thiel tells a giggling Cartman, â€œI came to see you in an Uber. You know how long it took me to get here? Around six or seven minutes.â€ Cartman starts laughing so hard that he projectile vomits all over Thiel. 

	Unable to complete the exorcism, he tells Ms.Cartman that he must take her child to D.C., and that â€œeverything we hold dear could endâ€ if he doesnâ€™t â€œunlock the secrets he holds.â€

	â€œ6-7â€ (pronounced â€œsix sevenâ€) is a viral lyric from the rap single â€œDoot Doot (6 7)â€ from American artist Skrilla. The phrase skyrocketed into the cultural zeitgeist through TikTok, proving especially popular with younger users. As demonstrated by â€œSouth Park,â€ â€œ6-7â€ is often recited in tadum with a hand gesture popularized by a TikTok user named Maverick Trevillain, fittingly known as â€œThe 67 Kid.â€ The phrase doesnâ€™t appear to have any real meaning and functions more as an internet inside joke.

	Thiel recently made headlines after the Washington Post published the contents of his invite-only, off-record lectures on religion and the tech industry. Across the four, roughly two-hour-long talks, the venture capitalist accused Greta Thunberg as well as all those who are critical of the rapid development of artificial intelligence of being â€œlegionnaires of the Antichrist.â€

title: Kevin Federline Speaks Out on Britney Spearsâ€™ Alleged Drug Use and Erratic Behavior, Opposes End of Her Conservatorship: 7 Biggest Revelations From New Memoir

body:
With his debut memoir â€œYou Thought You Knew,â€ Kevin Federline is telling his side of the story. The 47-year-old first came to public prominence as Britney Spearsâ€˜ second husband after they married in 2004, plucked from his rising career as a dancer and thrust into a chaotic world of paparazzi and superstardom. But things soon turned acrimonious following the birth of their two sons, Preston and Jayden, leading to years of infighting over custody out of concern for Spearsâ€™ mental health and his ridicule as a public figure.
	

	Federline outlines much of his experiences with Spears in â€œYou Thought You Knew,â€ out Oct. 21, while shedding light on his personal trajectory. From the start, the Fresno native reflects on his burgeoning dance career on tour with LFO and Pink amid his relationship with Shar Jackson, with whom he has two children. But much of his story focuses on Spears and their tumultuous romance, from the whirlwind of attention to their inevitably contentious dynamic. Through it all, he reiterates his devotion to being a father to his six children, stating that he only cares to protect them from the ills of the world.


	In a statement to Variety, a rep for Spears says, â€œWith news from Kevinâ€™s book breaking, once again he and others are profiting off her and sadly it comes after child support has ended with Kevin. All she cares about are her kids, Sean Preston and Jayden James and their well-being during this sensationalism. She detailed her journey in her memoir.â€

	Now living in Hawaii with his wife Victoria Prince, Federline traces the shocking moments from his life in â€œYou Thought You Knew,â€ divulging how it all unfolded.
	

	Federline Was Thrown Into the Deep End

	After meeting Spears at Hollywood club Josephâ€™s and sparking their romance, Federline was brought into her circle, as she demanded that her team include him on her European tour. Her security warned him to â€œbe carefulâ€ and that he was â€œon a sinking ship,â€ which he said was â€œthe first real warning,â€ but it was a night in Amsterdam that ultimately changed his perspective. They returned to their hotel room after a night of partying when Spears said sheâ€™d be right back. Federline later found her making out with a dancer named Theresa and swiftly packed to leave the tour, only to change his mind after she apologized. Still, he recalled, â€œthat moment was a turning point for both of us,â€ one where she realized that he wasnâ€™t there for the â€œfame or perks.â€

	Spears Had â€˜Unfinished Businessâ€™ With Justin Timberlake

	The night before Federline married Spears in 2004, he recalls that she had a phone call with her ex-boyfriend Justin Timberlake outside of where they were staying in Santa Monica. He said he could â€œtell Britney still had some unfinished businessâ€ with Timberlake, and that she had been crying. She explained that she needed to call Timberlake â€œto end one chapter of her life before starting a new oneâ€ and wanted closure. But â€œeven after the wedding, I could tell she hadnâ€™t fully moved on,â€ he writes. â€œLooking back, especially after hearing what she said in her book, I realize it was deeper than that. She never really got over him. She mightâ€™ve loved me, but there was always something there with Justin that she couldnâ€™t let go of.â€

	He Learned of Their Divorce Through an Interview

	Federline claims throughout his memoir that he had several breaking points during his relationship with Spears, but points specifically to one evening where he knew â€œthis was the beginning of the endâ€ for their marriage. In 2006, Federline was celebrating the release of his debut album with a party at Los Angelesâ€™ Paramount Studios on Halloween. Spears initially said that she would not be attending, but inevitably did show up along with her brother Brian, father Jamie, agent Jason Trawick and an unnamed actress. Federline walked in on her in his dressing room doing cocaine with the actress, something that heâ€™d seen her do before, but was shocked to witness as she was breastfeeding at the time.
	

	Federline confronted her about using cocaine, telling her, â€œPlease donâ€™t go home and breastfeed the kids like this. Call your mom or someone. We need to get formula. You canâ€™t do this.â€ Spears then threw a drink in his face and stormed off, while Federline called her mother and insisted that she not let Spears breastfeed at her home. The next morning, Federline called his lawyer Mark Kaplan to draft a legal letter demanding that Spears stop breastfeeding their children, and Federline left town to promote his record, ignoring her calls and messages. While he was in Toronto for an interview at MuchMusic, a producer asked him just before he went on air, â€œHow do you feel about Britney filing for divorce?â€ â€” the first heâ€™d heard of their split.

	He Details Spearsâ€™ Erratic Behavior Towards Their Children

	Federline spends much of â€œYou Thought You Knewâ€ insisting that his main priority has always been protecting his children and providing them with a safe life. But he writes of several instances where he claims Spears acted abusively and erratically around their two children. In perhaps the most shocking moment in the book, he describes how their sons Preston and Jayden awoke several nights to Spears standing in the doorway watching them sleep with a knife in her hand. â€œOh, youâ€™re awake?â€ she said, only to â€œturn around and pad off without explanation.â€

	The book also details several other incidents that his children relayed to him, including one where Preston claimed that Spears punched him in the face. Federline states that Spears bleached their hair down to the scalp, leaving them with burns, and that Preston once asked him when he was 10 or 11 why Spears kept forcing him to bathe with her. The boys recorded some incidents with Spears on their phones, including times that she verbally berated them and once woke up Jayden at midnight to put lotion on his face on a school night. He says that Spears also gave Jayden shellfish, knowing that he was allergic to it. In what Federline describes as another breaking point, Preston went to Europe with his girlfriendâ€™s family on vacation where he received a call from Spears, blaming Federline for everything. After Preston confronted her and called her out, Federline recalls, â€œHer response was chilling: she told him she wished he, his brother, and me were all dead.â€
	

	He Reflects on Spearsâ€™ Infamous Paparazzi Moments

	In her memoir â€œThe Woman in Me,â€ Spears explains that her split from Federline and severe postpartum depression led to her infamous episode where she shaved her head and attacked a paparazzoâ€™s car. Federline reflects on that period in â€œYou Thought You Knew,â€ describing the time that Spears locked herself in a bathroom with Jayden and claimed that Jayden was being abused at Federlineâ€™s house. After a standoff that lasted for hours, Spears was removed in a straitjacket and placed in a 5150 hold as their children were inspected by doctors due to her â€œoutlandish claims.â€ â€œI felt sick over what she was going through,â€ he states. â€œThis was someone I had loved.â€

	Federline Couldnâ€™t Get Behind the Free Britney Movement

	After Spears was put in a conservatorship, Federline says that he â€œsupported the decision because I believed it was the only way to stabilize her situation, and more importantly, provide a safer environment for our kids.â€ He turns his attention to the Free Britney movement, which rallied for her freedom from the conservatorship. â€œI tried to understand where they were coming from, but I could never fully get behind it,â€ he writes. â€œAt times, it felt more like a fandomâ€™s mob mentality than genuine concern for Britneyâ€™s well-being.â€ He theorizes that the judge who terminated the conservatorship in 2021 felt â€œpressureâ€ from the Free Britney movement, which â€œled the judge to ignore professional reports and cave to public opinion, especially with her own election on the line.â€

	When the conservatorship ended, he â€œbraced for the worst.â€ â€œThe Free Britney movement got it wrong,â€ he says. â€œAll of those people who put so much effort into that should now put the same energy into the Save Britney movement. Because this is no longer about freedom. Itâ€™s about survival.â€

	Heâ€™s Concerned for Spearsâ€™ Well-Being

	Though Federline has not spoken with Spears in years, he says that he feels â€œan increasing urgency that I canâ€™t ignoreâ€ and that her situation is â€œracing toward something irreversible.â€ â€œThe signs are all there: the erratic behavior, the isolation, the cycling of people around her, the refusal to accept help. Itâ€™s become impossible to pretend everythingâ€™s okay,â€ he writes. â€œFrom where I sit, the clock is ticking, and weâ€™re getting close to the eleventh hour. Something bad is going to happen if things donâ€™t change, and my biggest fear is that our sons will be left holding pieces. They love their mom. Theyâ€™ve seen the red flags. But they donâ€™t know how to help without being attacked, misunderstood, or blamed.â€

	The family suggested that her fans could make donations in her memory to a local food bank or an animal shelter. â€œShe loved her animals and she was steadfast in her support of the unhoused community, so any donations in her memory to a local food bank or an animal shelter would be a wonderful and much appreciated tribute to her,â€ the family told People.

	A friend said her health had â€œdeclined very suddenlyâ€ in the past few months, according to People, and that only her close family was aware, and chose â€œto keep things very private.â€

body:
A woman died in an â€œapparent suicideâ€ on Tuesday outside Disney Worldâ€˜s Contemporary Resort in Florida, according to the Orange County Sheriffâ€™s Office.

	â€œWe can confirm this was an apparent suicide,â€ a spokesperson for the Orange County Sheriffâ€™s Office told Variety in an email.

	The suicideâ€™s proximity to the famous Disney World monorail sparked unconfirmed reports online about the cause of death. However, a spokesperson from the Orange County Sheriffâ€™s Office told People that the victim was â€œNOT struck by the monorail,â€ and deemed any reports suggesting she was â€œerroneous information.â€
	

	Local outlet WKMG reported that local authorities received word around 6:40 p.m. local time about a body on North World Dive, which runs through Disneyâ€™s Contemporary Resort.


	A video by an onlooker posted online showed employees erecting a white pop-up tent on the terrace of the Contemporary Resort in the wake of the incident. Police cars can be seen congregating in the parking lot below.

	Originally opened in October 1971 as the Tempo Bay Hotel, the Contemporary Resort is one of the two original residences built at the Disney World Complex. On the Disney World website, the hotel is described as an â€œultra-modernâ€ lodging featuring the â€œiconic A-frame Contemporary towerâ€ and a â€œ90-foot-tall mural by Disney Legend Mary Blair â€” responsible for the distinct look and feel of the â€˜itâ€™s a small worldâ€™ attraction.â€

	The suicide comes a week after a woman in her 60s experienced a health issue and died after riding Disneylandâ€™s Haunted Mansion attraction in California. Anaheim Police confirmed that the woman was unresponsive after exiting the ride, and that Disneyland security administered CPR until first responders rushed her to the hospital. She was later pronounced dead.

SPOILER ALERT: This story contains spoilers for Season 2, Episode 7 of â€œGen V,â€ now streaming on Amazonâ€™s Prime Video.

	It turns out Marie (Jaz Sinclair) had a very good reason for originally thinking Dean Cipher (Hamish Linklater) had no powers: He doesnâ€™t.

	Toward the end of this weekâ€™s episode of â€œGen V,â€ Marie, her sister Annabeth (Keeya King), Cate (Maddie Phillips) and Emma (Lizze Broadway) look on in horror as they discover the elderly burn victim man they correctly assumed was Thomas Godolkin (Ethan Slater) has been controlling Cipher this whole time. It wasnâ€™t Cipher who had the power to control others, it was Thomas Godolkin. And from his hyperbaric chamber, Godolkin was controlling the man known as Cipher (who has no powers at all), and jumping in and out of othersâ€™ bodies as well, while he remained on life support. 
	

	Until, that is, Marie brought the century-old supe back to fighting form on this weekâ€™s â€œGen V,â€ in the hopes thatThomas Godolkin would help them stop Cipher. But too bad, he is Cipher! Now, Marie and Annabeth have Godolkinâ€™s pending massacre plans to deal with, on top of trying to mend their fragile sibling relationship: Annabeth confesses she knew Marie was going to kill their parents by accident before it happened, and itâ€™s haunted her ever since.




	

					Jaz Sinclair as Marie Moreau and Keeya King as Annabeth Moreau in â€œGen Vâ€ 
									Jasper Savage/Prime
	



	â€œSheâ€™s been completely removed from the supes, living with her Aunt Pam, and she thinks that supes are monsters. She doesnâ€™t fully grasp her powers, nor does she really understand them,â€ King told Variety abiut playing Marieâ€™s precog sister.
	

	And in her confusion over what happened to them and their parents, Annabethâ€™s pain and shame after their deaths turned into resentment toward Marie â€” she chose to blame her sister for something Annabeth knew was not Marieâ€™s fault.

	The twist in the sistersâ€™ story raises the stakes for not only Marie and Annabeth, but also for Cate, Emma, Jordan (Derek Luh/London Thor), Sam (Asa Germann) and Polarity (Sean Patrick Thomas) going into the â€œGen Vâ€ Season 2 finale next week. It shifts the perspective from what the audience saw in the opening scene of Season 1 â€”Â the deaths of Marie and Annabethâ€™s parents â€” and revealed thatÂ Marie is not solely responsible for her parentsâ€™ deaths. Annabeth could have said something and stopped it.

	â€œIâ€™ve watched the show, and Iâ€™m like, â€˜OK, Annabeth thinks that Marie killed her parents,'â€ King said. â€œAnd then when I sat down with our showrunner, Michelle, she actually explained to me the path that the writers had for Annabeth, which is that she actually had these visions and sheâ€™s been holding onto them for a very long time. 

	â€œAs an actor, itâ€™s sort of weaving in little moments of pain and regret of not acting on those visions, and then also sort of blaming my sister as well,â€ she continued. â€œBecause when youâ€™re upset with yourself, sometimes itâ€™s like, â€˜Where do I place that hurt?â€™ So sometimes she does place it on Marie, her sister.â€

Mark Ruffalo revealed on the â€œWhere Everybody Knows Your Nameâ€ podcast that he saved Woody Harrelson from an epic bar fight when the two were in New Orleans filming 2013â€™s â€œNow You See Me,â€ Louis Leterrierâ€™s heist thriller about a group of illusionists who carry out robberies. Ruffalo played an FBI agent trying to capture the group.

	â€œWe were shooting â€˜Now You See Meâ€™ in New Orleans, completely on the streets. Totally wild,â€ Ruffalo said (via Entertainment Weekly). â€œCapturing stuff on a long lens, getting dragged into bars during the middle of a scene, like in the middle of Mardi Gras.â€
	

	Ruffalo and Danson stayed out after filming wrapped for the day and went to â€œa packed placeâ€ to grab a drink when things escalated.


	â€œA woman came up to [Woody] and she said, â€˜Oh my God, I love you so much,'â€ Ruffalo said. â€œWoody put his hand on her arm and he said, â€˜Oh, thank you. Thank you, darling.â€™ And this guy comes over and he pushes her outta the way, and he shoves Woody. Bad. Because Woodyâ€™s first response is not â€˜shove someone back,â€™ but â€˜immediately punch them in the face.â€™ Which is the right thing to do, by the way. Itâ€™s the absolute right thing to do. But then a whole melee broke out in this bar. I was in the middle of it and it was turning into aâ€” it was getting to become a whole thingâ€¦ And I grabbed [Woody].â€

	â€œI grabbed [Woody] and I pulled him out,â€ Ruffalo continued. â€œBecause I was like, â€˜This could be fun, but it also just could go so disastrously wrong because you and I might be able to handle ourselves but the rest of the folks we were withâ€¦ I donâ€™t think so.â€

title: Alleged L.A. Palisades Wildfire Arsonist Indicted on Federal Charges
description:
L.A. Palisades Wildfire Fire
                          Feds Charge Alleged Arsonist Behind Firest
body:
L.A. Palisades Wildfire Fire
                          Feds Charge Alleged Arsonist Behind Firestorm
                      
                  
                        Published October 15, 2025 6:56 PM PDT
                                                                            
      
    
                  
          
                          
                
                  
      
    
          The man accused of igniting the catastrophic Pacific Palisades wildfire in Los Angeles has been hit with a federal indictment.
      
    
          According to the U.S. Department of Justice, Jonathan Rinderknecht was indicted Wednesday by a federal grand jury on three counts including two felonies. They're all tied to the New Yearâ€™s Day blaze that destroyed nearly 7,000 homes and businesses and caused an estimated $150 billion in damages.
      
    
          The indictment charges him with arson affecting property used in interstate commerce, destruction of property by fire, and timber set afire which are all serious federal crimes.
      
    
                  
          
                          
                
                                  
      
    
          Prosecutors say Rinderknecht intentionally set a brush fire in the hills above L.A. on January 1, which firefighters initially managed to knock down but days later, it reignited and exploded into what became known as the Palisades Fire, devastating entire neighborhoods.
      
    
          ]Rinderknecht will appear in Los Angeles federal court in the coming weeks. If convicted, he faces a minimum of five years and up to 45 years behind bars.

schema.headline: Alleged L.A. Palisades Wildfire Arsonist Indicted on Federal Charges

          Diane Keaton's family says she died from pneumonia ... and a longtime friend tells TMZ the actress' death didn't come as a surprise because she had been ill for a while.
      
    
          A longtime friend of Diane's told us she was struggling with an unnamed illness leading up to her October 11 death ... and the decline in Diane's health meant news of her passing was "not a shock" to the pal.

          Diane died this past Saturday at age 79 ... and as TMZ first reported, the L.A. Fire Dept. paramedics responded to her home around 8:08 AM, transporting one person -- confirmed by sources as Keaton -- by ambulance to a nearby hospital.

          Diane's family announced Wednesday the cause of death was pneumonia.
